'''Dumah''' ({{lang-ar|دومة}}; {{Lang-he|דּוּמָה}} ''Dūmāh''; [[Aramaic language|Aramaic]] for "silence") was the sixth son of [[Ishmael]], the son of [[biblical]] [[Abraham]] and [[Hagar (Bible)|Hagar]].

==Biblical references==
The generations of Ishamel are the ninth recorded in the [[Book of Genesis]]. In Genesis 21:18, the [[Mal'ak Elohim|angel of God]] promises [[Hagar (Bible)|Hagar]] and [[Abraham]] that their seed will forge a great nation and in Genesis 17:20, it is recorded that Ishmael produced 12 sons, the forefathers of 12 tribes. Dumah is sixth son of Ishmael and is mentioned in Genesis 25:14 and 1 [[Book of Chronicles|Chronicles]] 1:30.<ref name=Bromileyp995>Bromiley, 1979, p. 995.</ref>

==The tribe of Dumah==
[[File:Rajalil2.jpg|thumb|right|Ruins Near [[Dumat al-Jandal|Dumah]]: it is common practice in [[Saudi Arabia]] to fence archaeological sites.]]
In the [[Book of Isaiah]] ({{bibleverse|Isaiah|21:11|KJV}}), Dumah is mentioned in the context of [[Mount Seir|Seir]], which was associated with the territory of [[Edom]] in the Negev region. Attempts to locate the tribe named for and descended from Dumah have produced multiple possible identifications.<ref name=Bromileyp995/> A Dumah ([[Deir ad-Duma]]) in the vicinity of [[Hebron]] which is mentioned in [[Book of Joshua|Joshua]] 15:52 is one possibility. However, according to [[Geoffrey Bromiley]], the [[oracle]] concerning Dumah in Isaiah 21:11-12 seems better suited to a place in [[Arabia]], suggesting the site of [[Dumat al-Jandal]] as a more likely contender. Known today as [[Al-Jawf]], in ancient times it is mentioned in inscriptions of the [[Assyrian empire|Assyrian monarchs]] as ''Adummatu'' and is described as "a fortress of Arabia", "situated in the desert", that was destroyed by [[Sennacherib]]'s forces.<ref name=Bromileyp995/>

