'''Grigol Uratadze''' ({{lang-ka|გრიგოლ ურატაძე}}) (1880 – 1959) was a [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] [[Social Democracy|Social Democratic]] politician, diplomat and author. His name is also spelled '''Grégoire Ouratadze''' in a [[French language|French]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colisee.org/old/public//article/fiche/2501|title=Géorgie et France : Grigol Ouratadzé (1880-1959), secrétaire d'Etat|trans-title=Georgia and France: Grigol Uratadze (1880-1959), Secretary of State|language=fr|date=6 December 2014|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> manner.
In 1912, Uratadze, together with [[Vlasa Mgeladze]], was part of the Georgian delegation to [[Vienna]], where [[Leon Trotsky]] organized his short-lived union of [[Factions of the RSDLP|social democratic factions]] as an alternative to Lenin’s narrow notion of party unity.<ref name="Suny">[[Ronald Grigor Suny|Suny, Ronald Grigor]] (1994), ''The Making of the Georgian Nation'', p. 176. [[Indiana University Press]], {{ISBN|0-253-20915-3}}.</ref> A close associate of [[Noe Zhordania]], he figured prominently in the development of [[Menshevik|Menshevism]] in Georgia and took an active part in the establishment of an independent [[Democratic Republic of Georgia|republic of Georgia]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colisee.org/old/public//article/fiche/2495|title=La Ière République de Géorgie (1918-1921)|trans-title=The First Republic of Georgia (1918-1921)|language=fr|date=6 February 2013|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> in 1918. As a Georgian plenipotentiary in [[Moscow]], he signed a May 7, 1920 [[Treaty of Moscow (1920)|treaty]] with [[Russian SFSR|Soviet Russia]] in which Georgia’s independence was [[de jure]] recognized. The [[Red Army invasion of Georgia]] (1921) forced him into exile to [[France]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.colisee.org/old/public//article/fiche/1720|title=La Ière République de Géorgie en exil en France|language=fr|date=14 September 2012|accessdate=21 November 2018}}</ref> where he authored several monographs and numerous articles on the revolutionary movement in Georgia and the Soviet nationalities policy.
