'''Hiram Morgan''', born in Belfast in 1960, is an Irish historian. He was educated at St Patrick's College Knock Castlereagh County Down and at [[St Catharine's College, Cambridge|St Catharine's College Cambridge]] and currently teaches at [[University College Cork]]. He is an expert on the [[Nine Years War (Ireland)|Nine Years War]] (1594-1603), the career of [[Hugh O'Neill, Earl of Tyrone|Hugh O'Neill]] (1550-1616) and Ireland's connections with Europe and the wider world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hiram Morgan|url=http://publish.ucc.ie/researchprofiles/A019/hmorgan|publisher=University College Cork|accessdate=22 September 2015}}</ref> He was chairman of the [[Royal Irish Academy]] Committee for Historical Sciences between 2003 and 2007.
==Publications== His main works are: *Monograph: **Tyrone's rebellion: the outbreak of the Nine Years War in Tudor Ireland' (Woodbridge: Boydell & Brewer, April 1993), no. 67 in The Royal Historical Society Studies in History series.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Morgan|first1=Hiram|title=Tyrone's rebellion: the outbreak of the Nine Years War in Ireland|date=1993|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|isbn=0851156835|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yCow1u6qdMEC&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Hiram+Morgan%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=ExM4Vd32BYzdaJOJgNAN&ved=0CCEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Hiram%20Morgan%22&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Tyrone's Rebellion|url=http://www.boydellandbrewer.com/store/viewItem.asp?idProduct=12447|website=boydellandbrewer.com|publisher=Boydell & Brewer|accessdate=1 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McGurk|first1=John|title=Representing Ireland; & Tyrone's Rebellion|url=http://www.historytoday.com/john-mcgurk/representing-ireland-tyrones-rebellion|website=historytoday.com|publisher=History Today}}</ref> *Edited Books: **'Political Ideology in Ireland, 1541-1641' (Dublin: Four Courts Press, 1999).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Morgan|first1=Hiram|title=Political Ideology in Ireland, 1541-1641|date=1999|publisher=Four Courts Press|isbn=1851824405|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Political_Ideology_in_Ireland_1541_1641.html?id=_eiFAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McGurk|first1=John|title=Political Ideology in Ireland 1541-1641|url=http://www.history.ac.uk/reviews/review/98|website=history.ac.uk/|publisher=The Institute of Historical Research (IHR)|accessdate=24 April 2015}}</ref> ''Information, Media and Power through the Ages'' (Dublin: University College Dublin Press, 2001).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Morgan|first1=Hiram|title=Information, Media and Power Through the Ages|publisher=University College Dublin Press|isbn=1900621614|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=F5u5AAAAIAAJ&source=gbs_similarbooks}}</ref> ''[[Siege of Kinsale|The Battle of Kinsale]]'' (Bray: Wordwell Books, March 2004).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Morgan|first1=Hiram|title=The Battle of Kinsale|date=2004|publisher=Wordwell, Limited|isbn=1869857704|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QE0iAQAAIAAJ&source=gbs_similarbooks}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Smith|first1=Murray|title=The Battle of Kinsale|url=http://www.historyireland.com/early-modern-history-1500-1700/the-battle-of-kinsale-2/|website=historyireland.com|publisher=History Ireland}}</ref> *Translation/Scholarly Edition **With John Barry, ''Great Deeds in Ireland'', [[Richard Stanihurst|Richard Stanihurst’s]] De Rebus in Hibernia Gestis (Leiden, 1584), (Cork University Press, 2013).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Barry|first1=John|last2=Morgan|first2=Hiram|title=Great Deeds in Ireland, Richard Stanihurst De Rebus in Hibernia Gestis|date=2014|publisher=Cork University Press|isbn=1782050876|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Bzo3ngEACAAJ&dq=Great+Deeds+in+Ireland,+Richard+Stanihurst+De+Rebus+in+Hibernia+Gestis&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zBg4VbDRHIniarSNgfAL&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Serjeantson|first1=Dierdre|title=John Barry and Hiram Morgan, eds. Great Deeds in Ireland: Richard Stanihurst’s De Rebus in Hibernia Gestis|url=http://www.english.cam.ac.uk/spenseronline/review/volume-44/441/reviews-1/barry-john-and-hiram-morgan-eds-great-deeds-in-ireland-richard-stanihursts-de-rebus-in-hibernia-gestis/|website=www.english.cam.ac.uk/spenseronline|publisher=Spenser Online|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> *Journal **A founder and co-editor (1992-2002) of ''[[History Ireland]]'', the illustrated magazine dealing with all aspects of Irish history. *Websites **Morgan is director of the world’s largest online site for Irish Studies: [[Corpus of Electronic Texts|CELT]] ([http://www.ucc.ie/celt/ Corpus of Electronic Text of Ireland])
Some of Morgan’s own talks and writings are available @ https://ucc-ie.academia.edu/HiramMorgan
